==English==
===Etymology===
Middle English from Old French ''estable'' from Romanian ''stabula'' & Latin ''stabulum'' (''stare'' stand) <br>'''or'''<br> Middle English from Anglo-French; Old French ''estable'' from Latin ''stabilis'' (''stare'' stand [[-able]])

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-eɪbəl|-eɪbəl]]

=== Noun ===
'''stable'''
#A building set apart and adapted for lodging and feeding (and training) horses; racehorses of particular stable.
==== Translations ====
{{top}}
*Danish: [[stald]]
*Finnish: [[talli]] (1)
{{mid}}
*Swedish: [[stall]] ''n''
*Telugu: [[గుర్రపు శాల]] (gurrapu Saala)
{{bottom}}

=== Adjective ===
'''stable'''
#Relatively unchanging, permanent; firmly fixed or established, not easily to be moved, changed, unbalanced, destroyed or altered in value.
''He was in a stable relationship.''
==== Translations ====
{{top}}
*Danish: [[stabil]]
*Finnish: [[vakaa]] (1), [[tasainen]] (1)
{{mid}}
*Swedish: [[stabil]]
*Telugu: [[స్థిర]] (sthira), [[స్థిరమైన]] (sthiramaina)
{{bottom}}

